/* /find-an-accountant/colorado/ — t-state-pillar PILLAR. Colorado is a CORE state built to the 6-essentials depth
 * (pillar + quickbooks-accountant + small-business-accountant + quickbooks-cleanup + quickbooks-setup +
 * bookkeeping-services); every absent service/industry ROUTES TO GLOBAL. CO is an areaServed-ONLY state: TechBrot serves
 * Colorado remotely, so this pillar carries NO street address, NO PostalAddress, NO geo, NO LocalBusiness node, and NO
 * hasMap (all states are areaServed-only (no street address)). Service + areaServed (State of Colorado + named metros) only; provider =
 * #organization. Mirrors the PA/NJ/MD/VA/OH/MI/GA/NC/AZ/TN/WA core-state exemplars: OMITS `ecosystem`; `industries` cards ->
 * GLOBAL /accounting/industries/*; 5 SERVICE cards = the CO children; `cities` name+county with NO href; pricing rows ->
 * 5 children + global. Colorado continues Wave D (Denver/Boulder tech corridor / Colorado Springs aerospace / Front Range growth).
 *
 * COLORADO FACTS (verified 2026-06-26 against the Colorado Dept of Revenue and CO General Assembly — see _build/strategy/CO-FACTS.md):
 *  · The home-rule self-collecting city sales tax — THE CO-distinct hook and the most fragmented sales-tax system in the US.
 *    The state rate is just 2.9%, but counties, cities, and special districts (RTD, scientific/cultural) stack on top, so the
 *    combined rate commonly lands around 7-9%+ by location. About 70+ "home-rule" cities (Denver, Colorado Springs, Aurora,
 *    Boulder, Fort Collins, Lakewood, and more) self-collect — administering their OWN sales/use tax with their own rules,
 *    returns, and registration separate from the state. Many home-rule cities now participate in the state's SUTS (Sales &
 *    Use Tax System) single-return portal, but not all do, so some still require a separate return. Colorado is
 *    destination-sourced (since Oct 1, 2022). Specific combined/city rates kept qualitative.
 *  · The Retail Delivery Fee (RDF) — a per-retail-delivery fee on each retail sale delivered by motor vehicle that includes
 *    at least one item of taxable tangible personal property. $0.28 per delivery for July 2025-June 2026, adjusted for
 *    inflation each July. Qualified small and new businesses are exempt. The exact amount stays tied to the period.
 *  · Flat 4.40% income tax (individual AND corporate) for 2025 — UNLIKE Washington/Tennessee, Colorado HAS an income tax, so
 *    payroll DOES carry Colorado state income-tax withholding (Form DR 1098 / DR 0004). The rate is subject to a temporary
 *    TABOR-surplus reduction mechanism (it was temporarily 4.25% for tax year 2024, then back to 4.40% for 2025); confirm the
 *    current year with the Colorado Dept of Revenue.
 *  · SALT Parity Act (PTE election, SB22-124) — a partnership or S-corp can elect to pay Colorado income tax at the entity
 *    level so owners can deduct it federally (a SALT-cap workaround). Advisory/coordination only: the CPA makes the election
 *    (Form DR 1705 / DR 0106) and files; TechBrot keeps the books PTE-ready.
 *  · No local income tax — the local complexity is sales tax, not income (CO has no city/county income tax). A few cities
 *    historically levy a small flat occupational privilege tax (e.g. Denver's OPT) — a small per-employee head tax, not an
 *    income tax — mentioned only qualitatively.
 *  · Geography — 64 counties; the economy is Front-Range-centric. Metros: Denver (Denver County; tech, finance, aerospace; a
 *    home-rule city), Colorado Springs (El Paso County; aerospace and defense; home-rule), Aurora (Arapahoe County;
 *    home-rule), Fort Collins (Larimer County; CSU, tech, brewing; home-rule), Lakewood (Jefferson County; home-rule),
 *    Boulder (Boulder County; tech and startups, CU; home-rule), Pueblo (Pueblo County; manufacturing and steel), and Greeley
 *    (Weld County; agriculture and energy).
 *
 * HONESTY: TechBrot is an independent Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor + bookkeeping firm, NOT affiliated with Intuit. It
 * does NOT file CO or federal returns, the state or home-rule city sales/use-tax returns, the retail delivery fee return, the
 * income tax, or the PTE election as agent; it keeps the books and coordinates with the client's CPA/EA, the Colorado Dept of
 * Revenue, and the home-rule cities. Reviews are ONLY the 2 real Clutch reviews (Heidi Schubert, Barbara Best) — no invented
 * reviewers, no AggregateRating. Outcomes/scenarios are explicitly representative composites — never real-client claims. No
 * founder/personal name in visible content; David Westgate appears only as the named lead ProAdvisor/operator. The home-rule
 * self-collecting cities (~70+, separate returns/registration vs the SUTS portal), the 2.9% state sales tax plus local
 * layers, destination sourcing, the retail delivery fee ($0.28 for Jul 2025-Jun 2026, indexed), the flat 4.40% income tax
 * (2025; TABOR caveat) with CO state withholding, and the SALT Parity PTE election are VERIFIED and stated; specific
 * combined/city sales-tax rates and the next-year RDF amount are framed qualitatively. */
function stripTags(html){return html.replace(/<[^>]+>/g,"").replace(/&rsquo;/g,"’").replace(/&lsquo;/g,"‘").replace(/&ldquo;/g,"“").replace(/&rdquo;/g,"”").replace(/&mdash;/g,"—").replace(/&ndash;/g,"–").replace(/&rarr;/g,"→").replace(/&amp;/g,"&").replace(/&nbsp;/g," ").replace(/&middot;/g,"·").replace(/&times;/g,"×").replace(/\s+/g," ").trim();}

